{
  "text": "An additional motivation to this work, besides reducing signal clutter in brain activation studies, is that model-based assessment of baseline cerebral physiology could serve as biomarkers of certain cerebrovascular pathologies such as impaired dynamic cerebral autoregulation (CA). A current technology for CA assessment is transcranial Doppler ultrasonography (TCD), which can measure cerebral blood flow velocity in certain large intracranial vessels but cannot perform imaging [CITATION_1] . CA assessment with TCD has been explored in hypertension [CITATION_2] , severe carotid stenosis [CITATION_3] , vertebral artery disease [CITATION_4] , critically ill infants [CITATION_5] , and acute ischemic stroke [CITATION_6] . Modeling the CA response in fMRI and NIRS data is an exciting new frontier. Some of the parameters in the present model may also be altered during the progression of neurodegerative diseases. For example, changes in vascular stiffness in patients with Alzheimer's disease or vascular dementia [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] could be represented in the model as a decreased compliance parameter. Another example is diabetes mellitus, which is known to directly affect cerebral vasculature and to cause cerebral blood flow (CBF) abnormalities and complications of the cerebral circulation [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] . The detail included in the proposed model would allow for testing of specific hypotheses about the changes in physiology that accompany disease.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "11869541",
